threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The analyzed ELF binary is a DDoS botnet agent, likely a variant of the Gafgyt (Bashlite) or Mirai families, targeting MIPS-based IoT devices. It features a comprehensive command-and-control (C2) architecture capable of executing numerous network flood attacks, including UDP, TCP, HTTP, LDAP, NTP, and SNMP floods. The malware daemonizes upon execution, attempts to gain root privileges, and actively interacts with system watchdogs (/dev/watchdog) to maintain persistence by preventing reboots. It includes specialized attack vectors such as 'SendNUKE', 'SendOVH', and 'SendZAP', and uses a wide array of hardcoded browser User-Agents to obfuscate HTTP flood traffic. Concrete IOCs include the command strings ('INFECTED', '100UP', 'PAKI', 'NUKE') and references to watchdog devices.
